    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8eefc4d6_1886c385",
        "filename": "modules/particles/include/SkReflected.h",
        "patchSetId": 45
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-02-11T22:55:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Is this separate from the templated version so that SkCurve does not have to extend from SkReflected?",
      "revId": "ddabbf359803776758bc5299eb098cc5fd73ceee",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5b17e926_0e975a25",
        "filename": "modules/particles/include/SkReflected.h",
        "patchSetId": 45
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-02-12T18:29:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "More so that the gui visitor can intercept these to display the custom UI. However, I\u0027m realizing that if this were derived from SkReflected, I could have the template version also feed the Type (for SkReflected derived classes) to the visitors, and the default behavior would work fine. Then things like gui visitor could use the Type sidecar to detect and implement custom behavior. I\u0027ll worry about that in the future. (All of this code went through several revisions...)",
      "parentUuid": "8eefc4d6_1886c385",
      "revId": "ddabbf359803776758bc5299eb098cc5fd73ceee",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "806f51bb_26478d50",
        "filename": "modules/particles/src/SkCurve.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 45
      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-02-11T22:55:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Since nextF() is called every time, does it mean that as the curve is evaluated over time, a given \"particle\" will bounce between the min and max value at x? vs. each \"particle\" getting a random [0, 1] at spawn and then following that fixed interpolated curve between min and max? \n\nIf those two situations are clear enough, do you have experience as to which is most intuitive or useful for simulating particle effects?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 17,
        "startChar": 38,
        "endLine": 17,
        "endChar": 52
      },
      "revId": "ddabbf359803776758bc5299eb098cc5fd73ceee",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "739d524c_a8eb7af6",
        "filename": "modules/particles/src/SkCurve.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 45
      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-02-12T18:29:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It depends on which random is passed to the particular curve. In many cases, the random being passed here should be the stable random, so that each particle gets a stable interpolant. For curves evaluated over the emitter (vs particle) lifetime, the distinction doesn\u0027t really matter. In general, I think the stable version is more useful, although the last particle system I worked on also included a second layer of curve behavior that was essentially \"noise\" of different types on top of the authored curves.",
      "parentUuid": "806f51bb_26478d50",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 17,
        "startChar": 38,
        "endLine": 17,
        "endChar": 52
      },
      "revId": "ddabbf359803776758bc5299eb098cc5fd73ceee",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "37db6fc3_487d4a94",
        "filename": "modules/particles/src/SkParticleAffector.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 45
